{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"thesis","type":"file","file":"09 - Patterns and Theses/Thesis - Eyewitness Divergence in Transient Aerial Events.md","x":-200,"y":-500,"width":500,"height":260,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"legend","type":"text","text":"## Civilian / non-military witness incidents\n\nThe collection has four notable observations from non-military witness chains:\n\n- 1985 Papua New Guinea (multiple ground witnesses + Air Niugini pilot radar)\n- 1994 Kazakhstan (3 American commercial pilots, 40-min observation, photos taken, contrails persisted to next sunrise)\n- 2023 LiDAR Convoy CONUS (two FBI FD-302 interviews of contractor witnesses to same event with materially different descriptions)\n\nCivilian observations are evaluated under different epistemics than military ones: no SPEAR anonymization, no MISREP structure, but no formal training in identification of foreign aircraft and no instrumented sensor record.","x":-1300,"y":-500,"width":700,"height":520,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"png","type":"file","file":"02 - Incidents/Incident - 1985-01-24 Papua New Guinea Overflights.md","x":-700,"y":100,"width":450,"height":260,"color":"5"},
