		{"id":"w-rhodes","type":"file","file":"07 - Witnesses/Witness - Captain Ed Rhodes and Tajik Air Crew.md","x":-100,"y":650,"width":450,"height":200,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"w-a","type":"file","file":"07 - Witnesses/Witness - LiDAR Test Convoy Witness A.md","x":500,"y":790,"width":450,"height":180,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"w-b","type":"file","file":"07 - Witnesses/Witness - LiDAR Test Convoy Witness B.md","x":500,"y":1000,"width":450,"height":180,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"high-credibility","type":"text","text":"## Highest-evidentiary-tier civilian case\n\n==1994 Kazakhstan==\n\n- 3 American commercial pilots (former PanAm)\n- 40-minute direct observation\n- Photographs taken (Olympus pocket camera)\n- Contrails persisted long enough to be observed by same aircraft from below at sunrise 45 min later\n- Crew themselves proposed and rejected the meteor hypothesis\n- Diplomatic channel (DOS cable from Dushanbe)\n- 100,000 ft estimated contrail altitude\n\nThis is the single strongest civilian-channel observation in the entire collection.","x":-1300,"y":100,"width":520,"height":520,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"divergence","type":"text","text":"## Eyewitness divergence case\n\n==2023 LiDAR Convoy==\n\nTwo witnesses to the same event gave materially different descriptions:\n\nWitness A: ==linear metallic-gray object== with bright white light, 5000 ft AGL, bands visible within the light, structured shape\n\nWitness B: ==bright point of light== over horizon, 10-20 miles away, stationary then moved right, self-identified as ==probable meteor==\n\nThis is the cleanest illustration in the collection of eyewitness reliability constraints for transient aerial events. Disagreement is normal, not exceptional.","x":1100,"y":100,"width":500,"height":520,"color":"6"}
	],
